<div property="dc:description"><p>Nothing smells better than baked bread and it’s a living thing and it’s not often that you get to work with living things in a kitchen.</p>
<p>Our bread is magical. We don’t make white or brown bread, we make cakey, hot cross bun bread. It’s more like a museli bread, two bites are never the same.</p>
<noscript><p>
	It makes the most fantastic toast: big, thick and brilliant with a bit of butter. It also makes fantastic Welsh rarebit and, best of all, our bread matures for a day or two and becomes like Dundee cake so you never lose anything.</p>

<p>
	Any that&rsquo;s leftover after two or three days can be dried out, slice wafer thin and serve with soft cheese for a tasty treat.</p>

<p>
	It&rsquo;s a bread that you can use all year round and it&rsquo;s a big part of what we do, it&rsquo;s an extension of our food, it&rsquo;s that important.</p>

<p>
	However, I have no idea how to make it. In my experience, I have found that only certain people can make bread. You have to have a feel for it in your hands and in your heart. That&rsquo;s the way nature intended it to be: a magical thing for magical people.</p>

<p>
	Our magical person is Kate Johnston and here&rsquo;s her recipe for making our Michelin star bread.</p>

<p>
	Give it a go, it&rsquo;s expensive to make but it&rsquo;s a treat for everyone.</p>

<p>
<u><strong>21212&rsquo;s Michelin star bread</strong></u></p>

<p>
<em>3 pounds of bread flour (we use P55 but you can use any)</em></p>

<p>
<em>125g of butter</em></p>

<p>
<em>50g of yeast</em></p>

<p>
<em>A pint of water (tepid)</em></p>

<p>
<em>A tablespoon of sugar</em></p>

<p>
<em>2 tablespoons of water</em></p>

<p>
<em><strong>1 </strong>Mix the flour, butter, salt and sugar together in a mixing bowl</em></p>

<p>
<em><strong>2</strong> Add the yeast to the water in a separate bowl</em></p>

<p>
<em><strong>3 </strong>Add the yeast water to the flour mixture and mix together</em></p>

<p>
<em><strong>4</strong> At this stage you can add anything you want to the bread to flavour it. We usually add either a tablespoon of curry powder, 2 handfuls of sultanas, caraway seeds or pumpkin seeds but you can put whatever you want in.</em></p>

<p>
<em><strong>5</strong> Kneed the mixture for 7-10 minutes until you&rsquo;re left with a smooth dough.</em></p>

<p>
<em><strong>6 </strong>Put the dough in a bowl and leave in a warm place to double in size (prove).</em></p>

<p>
<em><strong>7 </strong>Roll the dough into either four loaves or however many small buns you want.</em></p>

<p>
<em><strong>8</strong> Egg wash the dough, add some garlic, onion and cheese to the top and dust with some flour and paprika.</em></p>

<p>
<em><strong>9</strong> Leave the dough to prove again.</em></p>

<p>
<em><strong>10 </strong>Cook the loaves for 25 minutes at 190 degrees centigrade. If you are making buns, cook them for around 10 minutes at 190 degrees centigrade.</em></p>

<p>
	This recipe makes four loaves.</p>

