<p>
<em>Bread comes in a variety of different styles and flavours, from sourdough to pumpernickel, but did you know that in Britain 70% of the bread eaten is white?</em></p>

<p>
<em>Here are 10 more fascinating facts that you might not know about bread.</em></p>

<p>
<em><strong>1</strong> The colour of the twist tie/tab on bread packaging indicates what day it was baked on.</em></p>

<p>
<em><strong>2</strong> Pre-sliced bread was invented in America by Otto Rohwedder in 1928. Rohwedder had spent 16 years working on his invention, which many assumed would be a passing fad because of concerns that it would go stale faster than unsliced bread.</em></p>

<p>
<em><strong>3</strong> Pre-sliced bread was banned in America in January 1943 by Claude R Wickard, head of the War Foods Administration and Secretary of Agriculture. It is believed the ban was introduced to help preserve resources and conserve wax paper. It was lifted almost three months later.</em></p>

<p>
<em><strong>4</strong> In Western Europe in Medieval times breads were named after the class of people who ate them. Examples include knight&rsquo;s loaf, squire&rsquo;s loaf and Pope&rsquo;s loaf.</em></p>

<p>
<em><strong>5</strong> The toaster was actually invented in 1926, two years before sliced bread.</em></p>

<p>
<em><strong>6 </strong>It takes nine seconds for a combine harvester to harvest enough wheat to make about 70 loaves of bread.</em></p>

<p>
<em><strong>7 </strong>Napoleon is credited with giving pumpernickel bread its name. During the Prussian campaign, Napoleon demanded a loaf of dark rye bread for his horse, ordering &ldquo;pain pue Nicole&rdquo;. However, to Germanic ears the order sounded like &lsquo;pumpernickel&rsquo;, which is now the term used for the bread.</em></p>

<p>
<em><strong>8 </strong>The inner part of the bread encased by the crust is called the crumb, hence why small bits of bread are called crumbs.</em></p>

<p>
<em><strong>9</strong> Bread is believed to have been invented by the Egyptians around 8.000 BC. It was used as a form of currency and was so important that loeaves were often placed in tombs for the deceased to take to the afterlife.</em></p>

<p>
<em><strong>10</strong> The average slice of packaged bread contains 1 gram of fat and 75 to 80 calories.</em></p>

